The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Lucknow, June 6 (PTI): The regional passport office in Lucknow will issue short-validity passports to Haj pilgrims. These passports will be issued only for travel to Saudi Arabia during the Haj period.           
	The directive came after the Saudi government decided to make passport compulsory for all Haj pilgrims, the regional passport officer said.                   
	 Mumbai: Shailesh B. Sheth, secretary of the Audit Bureau of Circulations (ABC), passed away in Mumbai on Friday. He was 54. He is survived by his mother, wife and two children. Shailesh B. Sheth joined the bureau in 1981 and served for 27 years. His family has arranged a prayer meeting on June 8.                  
	 New Delhi: Vice-Admiral Nirmal Kumar Verma will be the next chief of naval staff. He will take over from Admiral Sureesh Mehta on August 31. Verma is currently the flag officer commanding-in-chief of the Eastern Naval Command. Commissioned into the executive branch of the navy in 1970, Vice-Admiral Verma commanded the aircraft carrier INS Viraat, the destroyer, INS Ranvir, and the frigate, INS Udaygiri.                   
	 Mumbai: Padam Sinh Patil, the NCP MP from Osmanabad in Maharashtra, was picked up and taken to the CBI office in Mumbai on Saturday night for questioning in the case of his cousins murder. Pawanraje Nimbalkar was shot dead in his car in 2006.                   
	 Vienna (PTI): One of the six suspects detained for the attack on two Sikh preachers in Vienna in May has been released for lack of evidence. Three other suspects, including the alleged mastermind of the attack in which a leader of a Sikh sect was killed, will remain in custody, officials said.                   
	 Dehra Dun (PTI): Hundred spy cameras will be installed around various bathing ghats in Hardwar during Kumbh Mela early next year fearing terror attacks in crowded areas. Over five crore people are expected to take part in the annual bathing ritual.                                                                                                                           
